a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 In the diagram, $\triangle PQR$ is isosceles.  What is the value of $x$? [asy]
draw((0,0)--(3,6)--(6,0)--cycle);
draw((7,-2)--(6,0)--(8,0));
label("$Q$",(0,0),W);
label("$R$",(6,0),SW);
label("$P$",(3,6),N);
label("$x^\circ$",(6.5,0),SE);
label("$40^\circ$",(3,5.2),S);
draw((1.3,3.1)--(1.7,2.9));
draw((4.3,2.9)--(4.7,3.1));
[/asy] The final Answer is 70
 ### Proof
 Since $PQ=PR$, we have $\angle PQR = \angle PRQ$.
 From $\triangle PQR$, we have $40^\circ+\angle PQR+\angle PRQ=180^\circ$, so $\angle PQR+\angle PRQ=140^\circ$. Since $\angle PQR = \angle PRQ$, we have $\angle PQR = \angle PRQ = 70^\circ$. The angle labelled as $x^\circ$ is opposite $\angle PRQ$, so $x^\circ = \angle PRQ = 70^\circ$, so $x=\boxed{70}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x + 40 + 40 = 180"
shows  "x = 70"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

